            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.13.11"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">11</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">SCRIPPS COLLEGE
                        <lb/>
                    CLAREMONT âˆ™ CALIFORNIA</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 31, '27</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Neihardt,--</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thanks for your letter and its enclosure. I agree heartily with the whole program (which I s<del/><add>u</add>spect you of originating), and I shall be glad to help it along if that be possible. The tour in particular is a corking idea,-- and it has be<del><unclear>i</unclear></del><add>s</add>ides its possibility  of benefit in the line designed the further advantage of helping to break down some of the artificial ideas of college work that have latterly grown up within college fences. This old world seems to fossilize faster than it can grow -- turns to bone before its eye-teeth are out, so to speak,-- and anything that will tend to keep life a bit longer green (as your scheme should) ought to be welcomed.</p>
                
                <p>In a way it resembles what we have been doing at Santa Fe, only your idea is on a bigger canvas. I hope that the Santa Fe project may fit in with it some-how and perhaps become a part of the one movement.</p>
                
                <p>You may be interested to know that my Masks have been meeting with some reception from dramatically inclined people. I enclose some of Mrs. Wentworth's publicity of last summer, brought out after the Lake Tahoe performance. Later she produced them in several places in northern California, and received very fine notices. I am in hopes that she can get dates to carry them further. Is St. Louis possible? Ernest Thompson Seton told me last summer that he had been producing them, and I just have a letter from George Cram Cook's daughter, Nilla, saying that the Athenian Chorodrama is to produce one with Greek translation this feel. I am glad you like my new book's appearance, and I hope that the contents will not disappoint. I favored the limited art edition idea for the sake of Haugseth. I think his work amazingly fine and I am delighted with the reproductions Dutton has given.</p>
                
                <p>Scripps College is a new-born affair. It is too soon to predict, but everything <unclear><del/><add>is</add></unclear> youthfully hopeful now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>C<del/><add>o</add>rdially yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>HB Alexander</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note>Hartley B. Alexander</note>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
